<statement>
<p>Solve this system of equations using elimination.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}-{7}{y}={10}</m> </p>
<p>
  <m>\displaystyle{5}{x}-{4}{y}=-{12}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="8" /></p>

</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li><m>\displaystyle{\left(-{4},-{2}\right)}</m></li></ul></p><p>We chose (for no special reason) to use the first equation to eliminate x from the second equation.</p>
<p>To eliminate we need the scaled version of equation one to have a coefficient of -5. So we scale by <m>\displaystyle-\frac{{5}}{{1}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-\frac{{{5}}}{{1}}{\left({1}{x}+-{7}{y}\right)}=-\frac{{{5}}}{{1}}{\left({10}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{\left({5}\right)}{x}+{35}{y}=-{50}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{5}{x}-{4}{y}=-{12}</m></p>
<p>Adding these two equations gives us</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{31}{y}=-{62}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}=-\frac{{62}}{{31}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}=-{2}</m></p>
<p>Finally we can substitute this y value into the first equation to solve for x.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{1}{x}+-{7}{\left(-{2}\right)}={10}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{1}{x}+{\left({14}\right)}={10}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{1}{x}={10}-{\left({14}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{1}{x}=-{4}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}=-\frac{{4}}{{1}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}=-{4}</m></p>
<p>Thus the answer is <m>\displaystyle{\left(-{4},-{2}\right)}</m>.</p>

</solution>
</myopenmath>

